{
  "texts": [
    "Related to, but different from the task of generating novel protein sequences, prediction-focused protein language models are primarily concerned with predicting proteins' biological properties (e.g., 3D structures, functions) based on their AA residue sequences.",
    "Encoder-style language model architectures such as that of BERT are of particular relevance, as these models aim to learn the best representation of each token (i.e., AA) given the broader sequence context and thus can represent entire sequences in a meaningful, efficient manner.",
    "For example, Elnaggar et al. (2022) developed several LMs for protein sequences, including two autoregressive models (Transformer-XL, XLNet) and four auto-encoder models (BERT, Albert, Electra, T5) on data from UniRef and BFD containing up to 393 billion amino acids.",
    "Transformer Uniref90 MT from the Protein BERT project can be downloaded from the project GitHub repository (https://github.com/nadavbra/protein_bert) and protein sequences are embedded using the function in the protein Bert python package.",
    "Such representations can then be fed as the input to downstream predictive models, often also realized with neural networks (NN), for various tasks."
  ]
}